item.description:
arXiv:2607.19192v1 Announce Type: cross 
Abstract: Let $\Omega \subset \mathbb{R}$ be a bounded interval and let $PW(\Omega )$ be the corresponding Paley--Wiener space. For a measurable set $E\subset \mathbb{R}$ of finite measure, consider the largest possible fraction of the $L^{2}$-mass of a function in $PW(\Omega )$ that can lie in $E$. We prove that this concentration is no larger than the concentration attained on an interval of measure $\lvert E\rvert $. Thus, \emph{intervals optimize concentration in the Paley-Wiener space of band-limited functions.}
  The proof, based on an universality-type limit of the reproducing kernel of analytic trigonometric polynomials on the circle, has two steps. First, we establish an \emph{optimal concentration theorem for analytic trigonometric polynomials on the circle}. Second, the universality-type limit transfers the result from the circle to the real line, by controlling the expansion of circles whose projection kernels are midpoint Riemann sums for the Paley--Wiener sinc kernel.
